  "market_context": "Intraday session with YM in a downtrend after forming a failure swing; NQ concurrently made a higher high, creating SMT divergence. Analyst identified a mitigation block on YM as a potential short entry zone.",
  "key_observation": "NQ made a higher high while YM formed a failure swing and lower high, creating an SMT divergence that validated the YM mitigation block as a high-probability short setup.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Analyst identified a mitigation block on YM 5-minute chart formed by low-high-higher-low-higher-high sequence (not a breaker block).",
    "Step 2: Noted that YM created a failure swing (unprotected high) without sweeping prior highs, making the mitigation block low probability on its own.",
    "Step 3: Pulled up NQ chart and observed NQ made a higher high relative to YM’s high, confirming SMT divergence.",
    "Step 4: Concluded the SMT divergence meant NQ was stronger and YM weaker, so the YM mitigation block should act as resistance and trigger a bearish move.",
    "Step 5: Price retested the mitigation block zone and moved lower, confirming the setup."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reacted at the mitigation block and continued lower; trade was taken short with successful follow-through.",
  "lessons": "Mitigation blocks alone are low probability, but when paired with SMT divergence (e.g., NQ higher high vs YM failure swing), they become high-probability reversal zones for the weaker asset.",
